[Hepatitis A and hepatitis B are virus vaccine-preventable diseases, and hepatitis C is increasingly becoming controllable by medication. Hepatitis D virus is a helper-dependent defective RNA virus and only present in people already infected with hepatitis B virus. Chronic hepatitis B virus carriers are at risk of infection with hepatitis D virus. Hepatitis D virus is present worldwide and in all age groups. Its distribution parallels that of hepatitis B virus infection, although with different prevalence rates (high in many parts of Europe, Africa, and South America, but lower in China). Hepatitis D virus infection of chronically infected hepatitis B virus carriers may lead to fulminant acute hepatitis or severe chronic active hepatitis.

The Ministry of Health does not record the prevalence of hepatitis E virus infection in Vargas state. Hepatitis E virus is transmitted mainly through contaminated drinking water. It is usually a self-limiting infection and resolves within 4-6 weeks. Occasionally, a fulminant form of hepatitis develops with acute liver failure, which can lead to death.

A map showing the locations of the states of Venezuela can be accessed at http://reliefweb.int/map/venezuela-bolivarian-republic/states-venezuela. The interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Venezuela can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/3aDO. - Mod.CP]

